I've had very good luck with AliExpress so far but then again I buy the stuff that makes sense (it's usually stuff that's OEM only, or made in China to begin with). Ryzen 7500F, WD SN770X 2TB 2230, few miniPCs (Intel N97, Ryzen 6850H Pro, Ryzen 8845HS), a bunch of OLED panels and portable displays, gamepads, 512GB HP USB pendrive made by PNY (450MB/s write, 500MB/s read - £24 btw., now they're twice that 😂), retro pocket consoles, all sort of USB-C cables (all up to spec, ehich is kore than I can say than about my hit and miss on Amazon...) and 100-300W PD chargers, few 100W powerbanks from BASEUS specifically. The only lemon I've gotten were USB WiFi6E adapters that just had constant stability issues and turned out to be faulty product that didn't pass QC because I already have ones that worked. Generally speaking it's a gamble and if it's too good to be true, that's probably because it is. Be smart, buy from sellers that already sold a ton and have reviews that don't look like written by a bot or ai translator and you can keep the risk down.
The other issue I've had was seller not filling customs declaration so I was charged VAT twice and had to get refunded and another one where Evri (shitty UK courier company) crushed my parcel and didn't even attempt to deliver it and it was marked as return to the seller. Got my refund back as Ali points and ordered again 🤦🏻
On that note, wish me luck, just ordered new 3K OLED 16:10 portable display from Uperfect on November deals 😂
And at the end of the day you have to remember that some of the reliable, trusted budget brands you know today, started out as noname brands on TaoBao - Anker, Ugreen, ACASIS...🤷🏻
